[Reichsfreiherr](/Reichsfreiherr) Wilhelm von Innhausen und Knyphausen was, to put it mildly, a dedicated military man, having served the [Hesse-Kassel](/Hesse-Kassel) principality with a grim, unwavering focus from the mid-18th century until the dawn of the 19th. Born on 4 November 1716, in the rather obscure locale of [Lütetsburg](/L%C3%BCtetsburg), he would live to the ripe old age of 84, dying on 7 December 1800 in [Kassel](/Kassel), the capital of his home [Hesse-Kassel](/Hesse-Kassel). His career spanned decades, seeing him pledge allegiance first to [Prussia](/Kingdom_of_Prussia) from 1734 to 1775, before shifting his loyalty, or perhaps more accurately, his professional services, to the [Landgraviate of Hesse-Kassel](/Landgraviate_of_Hesse-Kassel) from 1776 to 1782.

His most notable command, and indeed the one that etched his name, however faintly, into the annals of history, was as second-in-command of the infamous [Hessian auxiliaries](/Hessian_(soldier)) during the tumultuous [American Revolutionary War](/American_Revolutionary_War). A conflict that, one might argue, was less about grand ideals and more about the brutal, grinding reality of men doing what they were paid to do.

Knyphausen's extensive service record reads like a roll call of significant engagements during that particular colonial unpleasantness: he saw action at the [Battle of White Plains](/Battle_of_White_Plains), the formidable [Battle of Fort Washington](/Battle_of_Fort_Washington), and the rather less glorious [Battle of Trenton](/Battle_of_Trenton). His strategic mind, or at least his tactical presence, was felt at the [Battle of Brandywine](/Battle_of_Brandywine), the aptly named [Battle of the Clouds](/Battle_of_the_Clouds), the chaotic [Battle of Germantown](/Battle_of_Germantown), and the tense standoff at the [Battle of White Marsh](/Battle_of_White_Marsh). Later, he would also be present at the [Battle of Springfield](/Battle_of_Springfield_(1780)) and the grueling [Battle of Monmouth](/Battle_of_Monmouth). A man who truly understood the subtle art of being everywhere at once, or at least, everywhere the British needed a steady hand.

This rather imposing figure, whose Wall Street residence during the Revolution speaks volumes about his temporary status and the nature of the occupation, was formally known as Wilhelm Reichsfreiherr [1] von Innhausen und Knyphausen [notes 1]. He was, in essence, a [German](/Germans) [general officer](/General_officer) who served the [Landgraviate of Hesse-Kassel](/Landgraviate_of_Hesse-Kassel), and found himself entangled in the [American Revolutionary War](/American_Revolutionary_War), leading the very [Hessian auxiliaries](/Hessian_(soldier)) that [Great Britain](/Kingdom_of_Great_Britain) so generously leased for their colonial endeavors. A mercenary, yes, but one of considerable experience and, by all accounts, a certain quiet competence.

### Biography

The foundation of Knyphausen's formidable military career was laid well before the American conflict began. His father, a colonel in a [Prussian](/Prussia) regiment, served under the legendary [Duke of Marlborough](/John_Churchill,_1st_Duke_of_Marlborough), suggesting a family legacy steeped in martial tradition and the pragmatic realities of European warfare. Young Knyphausen himself received his education in the vibrant intellectual and military hub of [Berlin](/Berlin), a city that, even then, was a crucible for strategic thought and disciplined training. It was here, in 1734, that he formally entered the rigorous [Prussian](/Prussia) military service, a path he would follow with unwavering dedication for over four decades. By 1775, his long and distinguished service culminated in his promotion to a general officer within the formidable army of [Frederick the Great](/Frederick_the_Great), a monarch whose military genius reshaped Europe. This period forged Knyphausen into an officer of profound experience and a keen understanding of military logistics and command.

However, his allegiance, or rather his contract, eventually shifted. In the army of [Hesse-Cassel](/Landgraviate_of_Hesse-Kassel), he held the rank of lieutenant general, a testament to his high standing. It was in 1776, armed with an impressive 42 years of military experience, that he embarked on a journey across the Atlantic to the nascent [Thirteen Colonies](/Thirteen_Colonies) of [British North America](/British_North_America). He arrived as the second-in-command of a force of 12,000 men, a contingent famously, and somewhat pejoratively, labeled "Hessians." These were not volunteers driven by patriotic fervor for the British Crown, but rather professional soldiers, often conscripted or hired, whose loyalty was to their paymasters in [Hesse-Cassel](/Landgraviate_of_Hesse-Kassel) and, by extension, [Great Britain](/Kingdom_of_Great_Britain). His superior in this expedition was [General Heister](/Leopold_Philip_de_Heister) [2], a figure whose own command would eventually be overshadowed by Knyphausen's steadfast presence.

Knyphausen's leadership of the Hessian troops was a constant feature throughout many of the pivotal engagements of the war. He directed his forces in the strategic maneuvers and fierce fighting at the [Battle of White Plains](/Battle_of_White_Plains), where American forces under Washington successfully disengaged. He was a central figure in the brutal assault on [Fort Washington](/Battle_of_Fort_Washington), a significant British victory that cost the Continental Army dearly in terms of men and supplies. His troops also participated in the larger, more sprawling battles such as [Brandywine](/Battle_of_Brandywine) and [Germantown](/Battle_of_Germantown), where the complexities of combined British and Hessian operations were put to the test. Later, he would lead elements in the skirmishes around [Springfield](/Battle_of_Springfield_(1780)) and the protracted, exhausting engagement at [Monmouth](/Battle_of_Monmouth). These were not battles for glory, but for tactical advantage, attrition, and the grim reality of holding ground.

Between 1779 and 1780, Knyphausen assumed a critical role, commanding British-held [New York City](/New_York_City), a vital strategic stronghold for the British forces. When his immediate superior, [General Heister](/Leopold_Philip_de_Heister), departed for Germany, Knyphausen naturally stepped into the void, taking command of all [German troops](/Germans_in_the_American_Revolution) serving under the overall British commander, [Sir William Howe](/Sir_William_Howe). This was a position of considerable trust and responsibility. Despite Knyphausen's seniority and undeniable experience, British officers held what were termed [dormant commissions](/Dormant_commission). This rather cynical arrangement meant that in the event the British commander became incapacitated or removed, a British officer would automatically outrank Knyphausen, ensuring that ultimate command remained firmly in British hands. Yet, even with this implied lack of full trust, Knyphausen's steady professionalism and strategic competence meant he was indeed trusted by his British superiors, a rare feat for an auxiliary commander.

A particularly telling episode in Knyphausen's service involved his regiment's participation in the pivotal attack on [Fort Washington](/Fort_Washington_(New_York)). Following this, his troops were garrisoned at [Trenton](/Trenton,_New_Jersey), in the strategically important colony of [New Jersey](/New_Jersey). Here, a critical error of judgment led to one of the most famous reversals of the war. Major von Dechow, an officer under Knyphausen's command, recognized the vulnerability of the town and wisely advised Colonel [Johann Rall](/Johann_Rall), the overall commander at [Trenton](/Trenton,_New_Jersey) in late 1776, to fortify it. Rall, notoriously overconfident and perhaps underestimating his American adversaries, dismissed this sound advice with a fatal lack of foresight. Consequently, during [George Washington%27s_crossing_of_the_Delaware_River) and the subsequent [Battle of Trenton](/Battle_of_Trenton), Rall's unfortified position became a death trap. Knyphausen's regiment, caught unprepared, made a desperate attempt to escape across [Assunpink Creek](/Assunpink_Creek) but was ultimately forced to surrender. Major von Dechow, whose warnings had been so tragically ignored, was mortally wounded during the chaotic engagement, a grim testament to the cost of hubris.

Beyond the debacle at [Trenton](/Battle_of_Trenton), [Sir William Howe](/Sir_William_Howe) entrusted Knyphausen with significant tactical responsibilities. At the [Battle of Brandywine](/Battle_of_Brandywine), a complex engagement in [Pennsylvania](/Pennsylvania), Knyphausen was given command of the right flank. His crucial task was to fix the attention of the Continental commanders along the main river line at [Chadds Ford](/Chadds_Ford), thereby allowing Howe's main force to execute a flanking maneuver. This required disciplined holding action and a calculated display of force to mislead the enemy. He also commanded the vanguard of the British army during its strategic withdrawal from Philadelphia, preceding the climactic confrontation at the [Battle of Monmouth](/Battle_of_Monmouth). His presence at the head of such a critical movement underscores the confidence the British command placed in his ability to manage a disciplined retreat under pressure.

For several years, the substantial majority of Knyphausen's command occupied the northern reaches of [Manhattan Island](/Manhattan_Island), maintaining a crucial British presence in the region. During the temporary absence of [Sir Henry Clinton](/Henry_Clinton_(1730%E2%80%931795)) in 1780, it was Knyphausen who stepped up to command the entire British-held [city](/New_York_City). [2] This was a period of sustained occupation, requiring constant vigilance and effective administration of a conquered populace. His regiment, a testament to its endurance, served continuously in the Americas from 1776, the year of its arrival, through to 1783, the very end of the war.

Knyphausen's departure from the North American theater in 1782 was not a matter of choice, but rather a necessity driven by his deteriorating health. Among his ailments was blindness in one eye, caused by a cataract, a cruel irony for a man whose profession demanded sharp sight. This personal struggle was compounded by the loss of his wife, who had passed away in 1778, leaving him with a profound sense of personal and professional weariness. [Friedrich Wilhelm von Lossberg](/Friedrich_Wilhelm_von_Lossberg) then took over command of the Hessian troops in New York, stepping into the formidable shoes left by Knyphausen.

Upon his return to Europe, Knyphausen harbored a profound sense of disillusionment, openly stating that he had "achieved neither glory nor advancement" through his years of service across the Atlantic. This was a candid admission for a professional soldier, reflecting the often-unrewarding nature of being an auxiliary force in a foreign conflict. However, towards the twilight of his life, he did receive a measure of recognition, being appointed military governor of [Cassel](/Kassel). He was widely regarded as a taciturn and discreet officer, qualities that served him well in handling his diverse and often reluctant troops. He possessed an innate understanding of the "temper of his troops," a critical skill when commanding a "hireling army" composed of recruits gathered from work-houses and by impressment, then hastily drilled in the rudimentary use of arms even while on shipboard. As Knyphausen himself frequently observed, such a heterogeneous and often unwilling force offered "little reliance" to a judicious commander; their numbers dwindled not just by death in battle, but, perhaps more significantly, by the persistent problem of desertion [2].

A fascinating post-war encounter occurred in 1785, shortly after the cessation of hostilities, when the revered [General Lafayette](/Gilbert_du_Motier,_marquis_de_La_Fayette) journeyed to [Cassel](/Kassel) and sought out Knyphausen. Lafayette, in a letter to [General Washington](/George_Washington), recounted their meeting, noting that they had reminisced about the war, exchanging polite compliments and recollections of battles fought on opposing sides [3]. It was a moment of mutual respect, a quiet acknowledgment between two professional soldiers, one fighting for a nascent nation, the other for a paymaster. Knyphausen's long and eventful life finally concluded in 1800, a direct consequence of complications arising from an eye surgery, a final, poignant footnote to a career marked by both vision and its eventual loss.

### Legacy

While Wilhelm von Knyphausen may not be a household name in American history, remnants of his presence persist, particularly in the defensive structures he oversaw. [Fort Hill Park](/Fort_Hill_Park) in [Staten Island, New York](/Staten_Island,_New_York), for instance, stands on the site of what was once known as Fort Knyphausen. This earthen redoubt was strategically constructed under his command, designed with the specific purpose of fending off persistent Patriot forces attempting to dislodge the British from their crucial holdings. It serves as a tangible, if somewhat overgrown, testament to his defensive efforts. Furthermore, a more subtle, yet enduring, recognition of his historical role can be found in the street names of [Glasgow, Delaware](/Glasgow,_Delaware), where one thoroughfare bears the name North General Knyphausen Court. These small, often overlooked markers underscore the indelible, if sometimes understated, impact he had on the American landscape during a pivotal period of its formation.

